          "Italian pairs pronouns constantly.",
          "When a DIRECT OBJECT meets an INDIRECT",
          "OBJECT, they fuse into tight clusters.",
          "",
          "THE TRANSFORMATION RULE:",
          "",
          "   mi, ti, ci, vi  \u2192  me, te, ce, ve",
          "   (before lo, la, li, le, ne)",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "",
          "   Mi d\u00e0 il libro.  \u2192 Me lo d\u00e0.",
          "   Ti mando la foto \u2192 Te la mando.",
          "   Ci porta i fiori \u2192 Ce li porta.",
          "   Vi spedisco le   \u2192 Ve le spedisco.",
          "      cartoline.",
          "",
          "The IO goes FIRST, the DO second."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Glielo dico io."
      },
      {
        "page": 2,
        "total_pages": 3,
        "content": [
          "GLI (him) and LE (her) behave differently.",
          "They merge with a DO into ONE FIXED WORD.",
          "",
          "THE GLIE-FAMILY:",
          "",
          "   gli/le + lo  \u2192  glielo",
          "   gli/le + la  \u2192  gliela",
          "   gli/le + li  \u2192  glieli",
          "   gli/le + le  \u2192  gliele",
          "   gli/le + ne  \u2192  gliene",
          "",
          "Same form serves 'to him' AND 'to her'.",
          "",
          "EXAMPLES:",
          "",
          "   Gli do il libro.  \u2192 Glielo do.",
          "   Le dico la verit\u00e0 \u2192 Gliela dico.",
          "   Gli presto soldi. \u2192 Glieli presto."
        ]
